# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: external-secrets
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:external-secrets/access-control] In physical security and information security, **access control** (**AC**) is the action of deciding whether a subject should be granted or denied access to an object (for example, a place or a resource).
[src:external-secrets/access-control] The act of *accessing* may mean consuming, entering, or using.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] It is often used interchangeably with authorization, although the authorization may be granted well in advance of the access control decision.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Access control on digital platforms is also termed admission control.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] The protection of external databases is essential to preserve digital security.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Access control is considered to be a significant aspect of privacy that should be further studied.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] **Access control policy** (also **access policy**) is part of an organization’s security policy.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] In order to verify the access control policy, organizations use an access control model.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] General security policies require designing or selecting appropriate security controls to satisfy an organization's risk appetite - access policies similarly require the organization to design or select access controls.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Broken access control is often listed as the number one risk in web applications.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] On the basis of the "principle of least privilege", consumers should only be authorized to access whatever they need to do their jobs, and nothing more.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Geographical access control may be enforced by personnel (e.g. border guard, bouncer, ticket checker), or with a device such as a turnstile.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] There may be fences to avoid circumventing this access control.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] An alternative of access control in the strict sense (physically controlling access itself) is a system of checking authorized presence, see e.g.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] A variant is exit control, e.g. of a shop (checkout) or a country.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] The term access control refers to the practice of restricting entrance to a property, a building, or a room to authorized persons.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Physical access control can be achieved by a human (a guard, bouncer, or receptionist), through mechanical means such as locks and keys, or through technological means such as access control systems like the mantrap.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Within these environments, physical key management may also be employed as a means of further managing and monitoring access to mechanically keyed areas or access to certain small assets.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Physical access control is a matter of who, where, and when.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] An access control system determines who is allowed to enter or exit, where they are allowed to exit or enter, and when they are allowed to enter or exit.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Historically, this was partially accomplished through keys and locks.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] When a door is locked, only someone with a key can enter through the door, depending on how the lock is configured.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Mechanical locks and keys do not allow restriction of the key holder to specific times or dates.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Mechanical locks and keys do not provide records of the key used on any specific door, and the keys can be easily copied or transferred to an unauthorized person.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] When a mechanical key is lost or the key holder is no longer authorized to use the protected area, the locks must be re-keyed.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Electronic access control (EAC) uses computers to solve the limitations of mechanical locks and keys.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] It is particularly difficult to guarantee identification (a critical component of authentication) with mechanical locks and keys.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] A wide range of credentials can be used to replace mechanical keys, allowing for complete authentication, authorization, and accounting.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] The electronic access control system grants access based on the credential presented.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] When access is granted, the resource is unlocked for a predetermined time and the transaction is recorded.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] When access is refused, the resource remains locked and the attempted access is recorded.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] The system will also monitor the resource and alarm if the resource is forcefully unlocked or held open too long after being unlocked.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] When a credential is presented to a reader, the reader sends the credential's information, usually a number, to a control panel, a highly reliable processor.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] The control panel compares the credential's number to an access control list, grants or denies the presented request, and sends a transaction log to a database.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] When access is denied based on the access control list, the door remains locked.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] If there is a match between the credential and the access control list, the control panel operates a relay that in turn unlocks the resource.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] The control panel also ignores an opening signal to prevent an alarm.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Often the reader provides feedback, such as a flashing red LED for an access denied and a flashing green LED for an access granted.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] The above description illustrates a single factor transaction.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Credentials can be passed around, thus subverting the access control list.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] For example, Alice has access rights to the server room, but Bob does not.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Alice either gives Bob her credential, or Bob takes it; he now has access to the server room.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] To prevent this, two-factor authentication can be used.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] In a two factor transaction, the presented credential and a second factor are needed for access to be granted; another factor can be a PIN code, a second credential, operator intervention, or a biometric input.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Passwords are a common means of verifying a user's identity before access is given to information systems.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] In addition, a fourth factor of authentication is now recognized: someone you know, whereby another person who knows you can provide a human element of authentication in situations where systems have been set up to allow for such scenarios.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] For example, a user may have their password, but have forgotten their smart card.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] In such a scenario, if the user is known to designated cohorts, the cohorts may provide their smart card and password, in combination with the extant factor of the user in question, and thus provide two factors for the user with the missing credential, giving three factors overall to allow access.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] A credential is a physical/tangible object, a piece of knowledge, or a facet of a person's physical being that enables an individual access to a given physical facility or computer-based information system.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Typically, credentials can be something a person knows (such as a number or PIN code), something they have (such as an access badge), something they are (such as a biometric feature), something they do (measurable behavioural patterns), or some combination of these items.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] This is known as multi-factor authentication.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] The typical credential is an access card or key-fob, and newer software can also turn users' smartphones into access devices.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] There are many card technologies including magnetic stripe, bar code, Wiegand, 125 kHz proximity, 26-bit card-swipe, contact smart cards, and contactless smart cards.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Also available are key-fobs, which are more compact than ID cards, and attach to a key ring.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Biometric technologies include fingerprint, facial recognition, iris recognition, retinal scan, voice, and hand geometry.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] The built-in biometric technologies found on newer smartphones can also be used as credentials in conjunction with access software running on mobile devices.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] In addition to older more traditional card access technologies, newer technologies such as near-field communication (NFC), Bluetooth low energy or Ultra-wideband (UWB) can also communicate user credentials to readers for system or building access.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Access control decisions are made by comparing the credentials to an access control list.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] This look-up can be done by a host or server, by an access control panel, or by a reader.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] The development of access control systems has observed a steady push of the look-up out from a central host to the edge of the system, or the reader.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] The predominant topology circa 2009 is hub and spoke with a control panel as the hub, and the readers as the spokes.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] The look-up and control functions are by the control panel.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] The spokes communicate through a serial connection; usually RS-485.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Some manufactures are pushing the decision making to the edge by placing a controller at the door.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Some readers may have additional features such as a display and function buttons for data collection purposes (i.e. clock-in/clock-out events for attendance reports), camera/speaker/microphone for intercom, or smart card read/write support.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] All the RS-485-related advantages and disadvantages also apply.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] The advantages and disadvantages of IP controllers apply to the IP readers as well.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] The most common security risk of intrusion through an access control system is by simply following a legitimate user through a door, referred to as "tailgating".
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Often, a legitimate user may hold the door for the intruder as an act of common courtesy.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] This risk can be minimized through security awareness training of the user population, or more active means such as turnstiles which admit only one person at a time.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] In very high-security applications, this risk is minimized by using a sally port (sometimes called a "security vestibule" or "mantrap"), where operator intervention is required, presumably after confirming valid identification.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] The second most common risk is from levering a door open by sheer brute force.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] This is relatively difficult on properly-secured doors with ruggedized strikes or high holding force magnetic locks.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Fully-implemented access control systems include forced-door monitoring alarms.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] These vary in effectiveness, often failing from high false-positive alarms, poor database configuration, or lack of active intrusion monitoring.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Most newer access control systems incorporate some type of "door prop" alarm to inform system administrators of a door left open longer than a specified length of time.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] The third most common security risk arises from natural disasters.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] In order to mitigate this risk, the structure of the building, down to the quality of the network and computer equipment is crucial.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] From an organizational perspective, the leadership will need to adopt and implement an All Hazards Plan, or Incident Response Plan.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] The highlights of any incident plan recommended by the National Incident Management System usually include pre-incident planning, during-incident actions, disaster recovery, and after-action review.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] An attack similar to levering is breaking through cheap partition walls, typically made of wallboard or cinder blocks.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] In shared tenant spaces, the divisional wall is a vulnerability.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] A vulnerability along the same lines is the breaking of sidelight windows located next to doors.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Spoofing of locking hardware is fairly simple and more elegant than levering.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] A strong magnet can operate the solenoid controlling bolts in electric locking hardware.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Motorized locks, more prevalent in Europe than in the US, are also susceptible to this attack using a doughnut-shaped magnet.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] It is also possible to manipulate the power to the lock either by removing or adding current, although most Access Control systems incorporate battery back-up systems, and the locks are almost always located on the secure side of the door.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Access cards themselves have proven vulnerable to sophisticated attacks.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Enterprising hackers have built portable readers that capture the card number from a user's proximity card.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] The hacker simply walks by the user, reads the card, and later presents the number to a reader securing the door.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] This is possible when card numbers are sent in the clear, no encryption being used.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] To counter this, dual authentication methods, such as a card plus a PIN should always be used.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Many access control credentials use unique serial numbers which are programmed in sequential order during manufacturing.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] In a method known as a "sequential attack", if an intruder has a credential once used in the system, they can simply increment or decrement the serial number until they find a credential that is currently authorized in the system.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Specifying credentials with random unique serial numbers is recommended to counter this threat.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] In addition, increasingly long lockout timeout intervals after a credential failure will make automated repeated attacks infeasible.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Finally, most electric locking hardware still uses mechanical keys as a fail-over.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Most conventional mechanical key locks are vulnerable to bumping.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] In computer security, general access control includes authentication, authorization, and audit.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] A more narrow definition of access control would cover only access approval, whereby the system makes a decision to grant or reject an access request from an already authenticated subject, based on what the subject is authorized to access.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Authentication and access control are often combined into a single operation, so that access is approved based on successful authentication, or based on an anonymous access token.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Authentication methods and tokens include passwords, biometric analysis, physical keys, electronic keys and devices, hidden paths, social barriers, and monitoring by humans and automated systems.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] In any access-control model, the entities that can perform actions on the system are called *subjects*, and the entities representing resources to which access may need to be controlled are called *objects* (see also Access Control Matrix).
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Subjects and objects should both be considered as software entities, rather than as human users: any human users can only have an effect on the system via the software entities that they control.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] In some models, for example the object-capability model, any software entity can potentially act as both subject and object.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] As of 2014, access-control models tend to fall into one of two classes: those based on capabilities and those based on access control lists (ACLs).
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Both capability-based and ACL-based models have mechanisms to allow access rights to be granted to all members of a *group* of subjects (often the group is itself modeled as a subject).
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Access to accounts can be enforced through many types of controls.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Discretionary Access Control (DAC) In DAC, the data owner determines who can access specific resources.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] For example, a system administrator may create a hierarchy of files to be accessed based on certain permissions.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Graph-based Access Control (GBAC) Compared to other approaches like RBAC or ABAC, the main difference is that in GBAC access rights are defined using an organizational query language instead of total enumeration.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] History-Based Access Control (HBAC) Access is granted or declined based on the real-time evaluation of a history of activities of the inquiring party, e.g. behavior, time between requests, content of requests.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] For example, the access to a certain service or data source can be granted or declined on the personal behavior, e.g. the request interval exceeds one query per second.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] History-of-Presence Based Access Control (HPBAC) Access control to resources is defined in terms of presence policies that need to be satisfied by presence records stored by the requestor.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Policies are usually written in terms of frequency, spread and regularity.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Identity-Based Access Control (IBAC) Using this network administrators can more effectively manage activity and access based on individual needs.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Lattice-Based Access Control (LBAC) A lattice is used to define the levels of security that an object may have and that a subject may have access to.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] The subject is only allowed to access an object if the security level of the subject is greater than or equal to that of the object.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Mandatory Access Control (MAC) In MAC, users do not have much freedom to determine who has access to their files.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] For example, security clearance of users and classification of data (as confidential, secret or top secret) are used as security labels to define the level of trust.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Organization-Based Access Control (OrBAC) OrBAC model allows the policy designer to define a security policy independently of the implementation.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Relationship-Based Access Control (ReBAC) A subject's permission to access a resource is defined by the presence of relationships between those subjects and resources.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) RBAC allows access based on the job title.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] RBAC largely eliminates discretion when providing access to objects.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] For example, a human resources specialist should not have permissions to create network accounts; this should be a role reserved for network administrators.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Rule-Based Access Control (RAC) RAC method, also referred to as Rule-Based Role-Based Access Control (RB-RBAC), is largely context based.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Example of this would be allowing students to use labs only during a certain time of day; it is the combination of students' RBAC-based information system access control with the time-based lab access rules.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Responsibility Based Access Control Information is accessed based on the responsibilities assigned to an actor or a business role.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Subscription-Based Access Control (SBAC) SBAC assigns permissions based on a user's subscription status, automating the process of granting, modifying, or revoking access as users subscribe, upgrade, downgrade, or cancel.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] SBAC is particularly relevant for SaaS business, where access to features, data, or services is tied to a user's active plan.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Unlike RBAC or ABAC, which define permissions based on roles or attributes, SBAC dynamically distributes roles and policies based on billing status, ensuring real-time access alignment.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Several regulatory frameworks impose specific access control requirements on organizations handling sensitive data.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] The HIPAA Security Rule requires covered entities and business associates to implement technical access controls for electronic protected health information (ePHI), including unique user identification, emergency access procedures, automatic logoff, and encryption and decryption mechanisms.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] The proposed HIPAA Security Rule update (NPRM, December 2024) would strengthen these requirements by mandating multi-factor authentication for all access to ePHI.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) Requirement 7 mandates that access to cardholder data be restricted on a need-to-know basis, while Requirement 8 requires unique identification for each person with computer access.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) addresses access control extensively in Special Publication 800-53 through the AC (Access Control) control family, which includes policies for account management, separation of duties, least privilege, and session controls.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] A technique used to define or restrict the rights of individuals or application programs to obtain data from, or place data onto, a storage device.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] The definition or restriction of the rights of individuals or application programs to obtain data from, or place data into, a storage device.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] The process of limiting access to the resources of an AIS (Automated Information System) to authorized users, programs, processes, or other systems.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] That function performed by the resource controller that allocates system resources to satisfy user requests.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] This definition depends on several other technical terms from Federal Standard 1037C.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] Special public member methods – **accessors** (aka **getters**) and **mutator methods** (often called **setters**) are used to control changes to class variables in order to prevent unauthorized access and data corruption.
[src:external-secrets/access-control] In public policy, access control to restrict access to systems ("authorization") or to track or monitor behavior within systems ("accountability") is an implementation feature of using trusted systems for security or social control.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Cloud computing and storage provide users with the capability to store and process their data in third-party data centers.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Organizations use the cloud in a variety of service models (e.g., SaaS, PaaS, IaaS) and deployment models (private, public, hybrid, and community).
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Security concerns associated with cloud computing are typically divided into issues faced by cloud providers and those faced by their customers.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] The responsibility is shared and is often described in a vendor's "shared responsibility model".
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] The provider must secure its infrastructure, while customers must secure their applications, identities, and configuration settings.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Analyses of large-scale cloud incidents indicate that many breaches result from misconfigurations and long-unremediated exposures rather than solely from zero-day vulnerabilities.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] When an organization stores data or hosts applications on the public cloud, it loses physical access to the hardware.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] As a result, potentially sensitive data may be at risk from insider attacks.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] According to a 2010 Cloud Security Alliance report, insider attacks rank among the top threats in cloud computing.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers must ensure that thorough background checks are conducted for employees with physical access to data centers.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] To conserve resources and reduce cost, cloud providers often store multiple customers' data on the same server.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] As a result, one user's private data might be viewable by another without proper isolation.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Providers implement data isolation and logical segregation to mitigate these risks.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] The extensive use of virtualization in cloud infrastructure brings unique security concerns.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Virtualization introduces an additional layer—the hypervisor—that must be secured and correctly configured.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] A compromise of the hypervisor management system can impact an entire data center.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security architecture is effective only if the correct defensive implementations are in place.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] An efficient cloud security architecture should recognize the issues that will arise with security management and follow all the best practices, procedures, and guidelines to ensure a secure cloud environment.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Security management addresses these issues with security controls.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] These controls protect cloud environments and are put in place to safeguard any weaknesses in the system and reduce the effect of an attack.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Administrative mechanisms intended to reduce attacks by informing attackers of consequences.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Controls designed to reduce vulnerabilities and prevent unauthorized access.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Controls that detect and respond to security events.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Includes monitoring, SIEM, IDS/IPS, malware detection.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Controls that reduce the impact of an incident and restore systems.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering is characterized by the security layers, plan, design, programming, and best practices that exist inside a cloud security arrangement.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering requires the composed and visual model (design and UI) to be characterized by the tasks inside the Cloud.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] This cloud security engineering process includes such things as access to the executives, techniques, and controls to ensure applications and information.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] It also includes ways to deal with and keep up with permeability, consistency, danger stance, and by and large security.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Processes for imparting security standards into cloud administrations and activities assume an approach that fulfills consistent guidelines and essential foundation security parts.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Though the idea of cloud computing is not new, organizations are increasingly adopting it because of its flexible scalability, relative trustability, and cost-effectiveness of services.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] However, despite its rapid adoption in some sectors and disciplines, research and statistics indicate that security-related pitfalls remain a major barrier to its full adoption.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] It is generally recommended that information security controls be selected and implemented in proportion to the risks, typically by assessing the threats, vulnerabilities and impacts.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security concerns can be grouped in various ways; Gartner identified seven, while the Cloud Security Alliance identified twelve areas of concern.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Cloud access security brokers (CASBs) are software that sits between cloud users and cloud applications to provide visibility into cloud application usage, data protection and governance to monitor all activity and enforce security policies.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Any service without a "hardened" environment is considered a "soft" target.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be protected just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] "Data loss or leakage represents 24.6 % and cloud-related malware 3.4 % of threats causing cloud outages".
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Every enterprise will have its own identity management system to control access to information and computing resources.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers either integrate the customer's identity management system into their own infrastructure, using federation or SSO technology or a biometric-based identification system, or provide an identity management system of their own.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers physically secure the IT hardware (servers, routers, cables etc.) against unauthorized access, interference, theft, fire, flood etc., and ensure that essential supplies (such as electricity) are sufficiently robust to minimise the possibility of disruption.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Various information security concerns relating to personnel involved in cloud services are typically handled through screening, security-awareness training, and role-based access controls.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Providers ensure that all critical data (credit-card numbers, for example) are masked or encrypted and that only authorised users have access to data in its entirety.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Moreover, digital identities and credentials must be protected as must any data that the provider collects or produces about customer activity in the cloud.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Penetration testing is the process of performing offensive security tests on a system, service, or computer network to find security weaknesses in it.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Since the cloud is a shared environment with other customers or tenants, following penetration-testing rules of engagement step-by-step is a mandatory requirement.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Scanning and penetration-testing from inside or outside the cloud should be authorised by the cloud provider.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Scanning the cloud from outside and inside using free or commercial tools is crucial.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Without a hardened environment, your service is considered a soft target.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be hardened just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Privacy legislation often varies by country.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] By having information stored via the cloud it is difficult to determine under which jurisdiction the data falls.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Trans-border clouds are popular given that the largest companies transcend several countries.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Legal dilemmas from the ambiguity of the cloud refer to how there is a difference in data-sharing law between and inside organisations.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Due to the autonomous nature of the cloud, consumers are often given management interfaces to monitor their databases.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] By having controls in one central location and by having the interface be easily accessible for user convenience, there is a possibility that a single actor could gain access to the cloud's management interface; giving them control over much of the system.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] The cloud's use of resource pooling means memory or storage resources may be recycled to another user.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] It is possible for current users to access information left by previous ones.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Cloud services require internet connectivity and use internet protocols, making them subject to attacks such as man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Furthermore, heavy reliance on internet connectivity means service disruptions or outages can cut off users entirely.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] As encryption algorithms age, vulnerabilities arise.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers must stay current with encryption standards and transition older systems before they become compromised.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Some advanced encryption algorithms applied to cloud computing increase the protection of privacy.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] In a practice called crypto-shredding, encryption keys can be deleted when data is no longer used.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Attribute-based encryption is a form of public-key encryption in which the user's secret key and the ciphertext depend on attributes (e.g., the country the user lives in, or their subscription type).
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] In such systems, access to decryption depends not simply on identity but on attributes.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Some of the strengths of ABE are that it bypasses the need for explicit key sharing (as in traditional PKI) and identity-based encryption (IBE).
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] However, ABE suffers from key-redistribution complexity: since decryption keys depend on attributes rather than identities, malicious users might leak attribute information, enabling unauthorized access.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] In CP-ABE, the encryptor controls the access policy for the ciphertext.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] The process includes Setup, Encrypt, KeyGen, and Decrypt algorithms; the encryptor defines an access structure that must match a user's attributes before decryption is allowed.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] In KP-ABE, the sender encrypts under a set of attributes, and the user's private key is issued to match a policy describing which ciphertexts they may decrypt.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] KP-ABE shifts access-control responsibility partially to the key-issuer rather than the encryptor.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] While it provides flexibility, the policy disclosure may weaken privacy guarantees.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Fully Homomorphic Encryption allows arbitrary computation on ciphertext without decryption.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] It is emerging as a high-security option for cloud environments, including voting systems.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] While promising, it remains largely experimental.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Searchable encryption enables secure search on encrypted data.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] It has symmetric and public-key variants.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] While it supports functionality over encrypted data, it introduces extra attack surfaces, especially when attribute indexing is involved.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Numerous laws and regulations govern the storage and use of data.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Similar standards exist in other jurisdictions (e.g., Singapore's Multi-Tier Cloud Security Standard).
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Similar laws may apply in different legal jurisdictions and may differ markedly from those in the US.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service users must often understand the legal and regulatory differences between the jurisdictions.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] For example, data stored by a cloud service provider (CSP) may be located in, say, Singapore and mirrored in the US.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] plans in place to ensure service continuity and data protection.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] In addition to the requirements on customers, data centers used by cloud providers may be subject to additional compliance obligations.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Using a cloud service provider (CSP) can lead to extra security concerns around data jurisdiction since customer or tenant data may not remain in the same location or provider's cloud.
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] These issues are typically addressed in service-level agreements (SLAs).
[src:external-secrets/cloud-computing-security] Legal issues may also include records-keeping requirements in the public sector, where agencies must retain and make available electronic records in a specific fashion.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] In cryptography, **encryption** (more specifically, encoding) is the process of transforming information in a way that, ideally, only authorized parties can decode.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] This process converts the original representation of the information, known as plaintext, into an alternative form known as ciphertext.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Despite its goal, encryption does not itself prevent interference but denies the intelligible content to a would-be interceptor.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] For technical reasons, an encryption scheme usually uses a pseudo-random encryption key generated by an algorithm.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] It is possible to decrypt the message without possessing the key but, for a well-designed encryption scheme, considerable computational resources and skills are required.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] An authorized recipient can easily decrypt the message with the key provided by the originator to recipients but not to unauthorized users.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Historically, various forms of encryption have been used to aid in cryptography.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Early encryption techniques were often used in military messaging.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Since then, new techniques have emerged and become commonplace in all areas of modern computing.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Modern encryption schemes use the concepts of public-key and symmetric-key.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Modern encryption techniques ensure security because modern computers are inefficient at cracking the encryption.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] One of the earliest forms of encryption is symbol replacement, which was first found in the tomb of Khnumhotep II, who lived in 1900 BC Egypt.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Symbol replacement encryption is "non-standard," which means that the symbols require a cipher or key to understand.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] This type of early encryption was used throughout Ancient Greece and Rome for military purposes.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] One of the most famous military encryption developments was the Caesar cipher, in which a plaintext letter is shifted a fixed number of positions along the alphabet to get the encoded letter.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] A message encoded with this type of encryption could be decoded with a fixed number on the Caesar cipher.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Around 800 AD, Arab mathematician al-Kindi developed the technique of frequency analysis – which was an attempt to crack ciphers systematically, including the Caesar cipher.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] This technique looked at the frequency of letters in the encrypted message to determine the appropriate shift: for example, the most common letter in English text is E and is therefore likely to be represented by the letter that appears most commonly in the ciphertext.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] This technique was rendered ineffective by the polyalphabetic cipher, described by al-Qalqashandi (1355–1418) and Leon Battista Alberti (in 1465), which varied the substitution alphabet as encryption proceeded in order to confound such analysis.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Around 1790, Thomas Jefferson theorized a cipher to encode and decode messages to provide a more secure way of military correspondence.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] The cipher, known today as the Wheel Cipher or the Jefferson Disk, although never actually built, was theorized as a spool that could jumble an English message up to 36 characters.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] The message could be decrypted by plugging in the jumbled message to a receiver with an identical cipher.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] A similar device to the Jefferson Disk, the M-94, was developed in 1917 independently by US Army Major Joseph Mauborne.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] This device was used in U.S. military communications until 1942.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] In World War II, the Axis powers used a more advanced version of the M-94 called the Enigma Machine.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] The Enigma Machine was more complex because unlike the Jefferson Wheel and the M-94, each day the jumble of letters switched to a completely new combination.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Each day's combination was only known by the Axis, so many thought the only way to break the code would be to try over 17,000 combinations within 24 hours.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] The Allies used computing power to severely limit the number of reasonable combinations they needed to check every day, leading to the breaking of the Enigma Machine.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Today, encryption is used in the transfer of communication over the Internet for security and commerce.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] As computing power continues to increase, computer encryption is constantly evolving to prevent eavesdropping attacks.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] One of the first "modern" cipher suites, DES, used a 56-bit key with 72,057,594,037,927,936 possibilities; it was cracked in 1999 by EFF's brute-force DES cracker, which required 22 hours and 15 minutes to do so.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Modern encryption standards often use stronger key sizes, such as AES (256-bit mode), TwoFish, ChaCha20-Poly1305, Serpent (configurable up to 512-bit).
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Cipher suites that use a 128-bit or higher key, like AES, cannot be brute-forced because the total number of keys is 3.4028237e+38 possibilities.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] The most likely option for cracking ciphers with large key sizes is to find vulnerabilities in the cipher itself, like inherent biases and backdoors or by exploiting physical side effects through Side-channel attacks.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] For example, RC4, a stream cipher, was cracked due to inherent biases and vulnerabilities in the cipher.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] In the context of cryptography, encryption serves as a mechanism to ensure confidentiality.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Since data may be visible on the Internet, sensitive information such as passwords and personal communication may be exposed to potential interceptors.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] The process of encrypting and decrypting messages involves keys.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] The two main types of keys in cryptographic systems are symmetric-key and public-key (also known as asymmetric-key).
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Many complex cryptographic algorithms often use simple modular arithmetic in their implementations.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] In symmetric-key schemes, the encryption and decryption keys are the same.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Communicating parties must have the same key in order to achieve secure communication.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] The German Enigma Machine used a new symmetric-key each day for encoding and decoding messages.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] In public-key cryptography schemes, the encryption key is published for anyone to use and encrypt messages.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] However, only the receiving party has access to the decryption key that enables messages to be read.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Public-key encryption was first described in a secret document in 1973; beforehand, all encryption schemes were symmetric-key (also called private-key).
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Although published subsequently, the work of Diffie and Hellman was published in a journal with a large readership, and the value of the methodology was explicitly described.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] The method became known as the Diffie-Hellman key exchange.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] RSA (Rivest–Shamir–Adleman) is another notable public-key cryptosystem.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Created in 1978, it is still used today for applications involving digital signatures.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Using number theory, the RSA algorithm selects two prime numbers, which help generate both the encryption and decryption keys.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] A publicly available public-key encryption application called Pretty Good Privacy (PGP) was written in 1991 by Phil Zimmermann, and distributed free of charge with source code.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] PGP was purchased by Symantec in 2010 and is regularly updated.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Encryption has long been used by militaries and governments to facilitate secret communication.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] It is now commonly used in protecting information within many kinds of civilian systems.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] For example, the Computer Security Institute reported that in 2007, 71% of companies surveyed used encryption for some of their data in transit, and 53% used encryption for some of their data in storage.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Encryption can be used to protect data "at rest", such as information stored on computers and storage devices (e.g.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] In recent years, there have been numerous reports of confidential data, such as customers' personal records, being exposed through loss or theft of laptops or backup drives; encrypting such files at rest helps protect them if physical security measures fail.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Digital rights management systems, which prevent unauthorized use or reproduction of copyrighted material and protect software against reverse engineering (see also copy protection), is another somewhat different example of using encryption on data at rest.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Encryption is also used to protect data in transit, for example data being transferred via networks (e.g. the Internet, e-commerce), mobile telephones, wireless microphones, wireless intercom systems, Bluetooth devices and bank automatic teller machines.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] There have been numerous reports of data in transit being intercepted in recent years.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Data should also be encrypted when transmitted across networks in order to protect against eavesdropping of network traffic by unauthorized users.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Encryption plays a central role in meeting regulatory requirements for the protection of sensitive data.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Under the HIPAA Security Rule, encryption of electronic protected health information (ePHI) is classified as an "addressable" implementation specification, meaning covered entities must implement it or document why an equivalent alternative measure is reasonable and appropriate.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Notably, the HIPAA Breach Notification Rule provides a safe harbor for encrypted data: breaches involving ePHI that has been encrypted in accordance with NIST standards are not considered reportable breaches.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] A proposed update to the HIPAA Security Rule (NPRM, December 2024) would make encryption of ePHI at rest and in transit a mandatory requirement, removing its current "addressable" status.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) requires encryption of cardholder data both in storage (Requirement 3) and during transmission over open public networks (Requirement 4), specifying the use of strong cryptographic algorithms.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Conventional methods for permanently deleting data from a storage device involve overwriting the device's whole content with zeros, ones, or other patterns – a process which can take a significant amount of time, depending on the capacity and the type of storage medium.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Cryptography offers a way of making the erasure almost instantaneous.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] An example implementation of this method can be found on iOS devices, where the cryptographic key is kept in a dedicated 'effaceable storage'.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Because the key is stored on the same device, this setup on its own does not offer full privacy or security protection if an unauthorized person gains physical access to the device.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Encryption is used in the 21st century to protect digital data and information systems.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] As computing power increased over the years, encryption technology has only become more advanced and secure.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] However, this advancement in technology has also exposed a potential limitation of today's encryption methods.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] The length of the encryption key is an indicator of the strength of the encryption method.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] For example, the original encryption key, DES (Data Encryption Standard), was 56 bits, meaning it had 2^56 combination possibilities.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] With today's computing power, a 56-bit key is no longer secure, being vulnerable to brute force attacks.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Quantum computing uses properties of quantum mechanics in order to process large amounts of data simultaneously.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Quantum computing has been found to achieve computing speeds thousands of times faster than today's supercomputers.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] This computing power presents a challenge to today's encryption technology.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] For example, RSA encryption uses the multiplication of very large prime numbers to create a semiprime number for its public key.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Decoding this key without its private key requires this semiprime number to be factored, which can take a very long time to do with modern computers.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] It would take a supercomputer anywhere between weeks to months to factor in this key.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] However, quantum computing can use quantum algorithms to factor this semiprime number in the same amount of time it takes for normal computers to generate it.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] This would make all data protected by current public-key encryption vulnerable to quantum computing attacks.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Other encryption techniques like elliptic curve cryptography and symmetric key encryption are also vulnerable to quantum computing.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] While quantum computing could be a threat to encryption security in the future, quantum computing as it currently stands is still very limited.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Quantum computing currently is not commercially available, cannot handle large amounts of code, and only exists as computational devices, not computers.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Furthermore, quantum computing advancements will be able to be used in favor of encryption as well.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] The National Security Agency (NSA) is currently preparing post-quantum encryption standards for the future.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Quantum encryption promises a level of security that will be able to counter the threat of quantum computing.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Encryption is an important tool but is not sufficient alone to ensure the security or privacy of sensitive information throughout its lifetime.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Most applications of encryption protect information only at rest or in transit, leaving sensitive data in clear text and potentially vulnerable to improper disclosure during processing, such as by a cloud service for example.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Homomorphic encryption and secure multi-party computation are emerging techniques to compute encrypted data; these techniques are general and Turing complete but incur high computational and/or communication costs.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] In response to encryption of data at rest, cyber-adversaries have developed new types of attacks.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] These more recent threats to encryption of data at rest include cryptographic attacks, stolen ciphertext attacks, attacks on encryption keys, insider attacks, data corruption or integrity attacks, data destruction attacks, and ransomware attacks.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Data fragmentation and active defense data protection technologies attempt to counter some of these attacks, by distributing, moving, or mutating ciphertext so it is more difficult to identify, steal, corrupt, or destroy.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] The question of balancing the need for national security with the right to privacy has been debated for years, since encryption has become critical in today's digital society.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] The modern encryption debate started around the '90s when US government tried to ban cryptography because, according to them, it would threaten national security.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] The debate is polarized around two opposing views.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Those who see strong encryption as a problem making it easier for criminals to hide their illegal acts online and others who argue that encryption keep digital communications safe.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] The debate heated up in 2014, when Big Tech like Apple and Google set encryption by default in their devices.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] This was the start of a series of controversies that puts governments, companies and internet users at stake.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Authenticated encryption algorithms are designed to provide both encryption and integrity protection together.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Standards for cryptographic software and hardware to perform encryption are widely available, but successfully using encryption to ensure security may be a challenging problem.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] A single error in system design or execution can allow successful attacks.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Sometimes an adversary can obtain unencrypted information without directly undoing the encryption.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] See for example traffic analysis, TEMPEST, or Trojan horse.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Encrypting at the time of creation is only secure if the encryption device itself has correct keys and has not been tampered with.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] If an endpoint device has been configured to trust a root certificate that an attacker controls, for example, then the attacker can both inspect and tamper with encrypted data by performing a man-in-the-middle attack anywhere along the message's path.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] The common practice of TLS interception by network operators represents a controlled and institutionally sanctioned form of such an attack, but countries have also attempted to employ such attacks as a form of control and censorship.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Even when encryption effectively conceals a message’s content and prevents tampering, the *length* of the ciphertext remains a form of metadata that can leak sensitive information.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] For instance, the well-known CRIME and BREACH attacks against HTTPS exploited information leakage through encrypted message length as a side-channel attack.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Traffic analysis more broadly refers to techniques that use metadata—such as message size and timing—to infer information about communication patterns.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Applying padding to a message before encryption can help obscure its true plaintext length, though this increases the ciphertext size and adds bandwidth overhead.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Padding may be applied randomly or deterministically, each approach involving different trade-offs.
[src:external-secrets/encryption] Encrypting and padding data to produce padded uniform random blobs (PURBs) ensures that the ciphertext reveals no metadata about the plaintext’s structure, leaking only asymptotically minimal $O(\log \log M)$ information through its length.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] The terms "identity management" (IdM) and "identity and access management" are used interchangeably in the area of identity access management.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] Identity-management systems, products, applications and platforms manage identifying and ancillary data about entities that include individuals, computer-related hardware, and software applications.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] IdM covers issues such as how users gain an identity, the roles, and sometimes the permissions that identity grants, the protection of that identity, and the technologies supporting that protection (e.g., network protocols, digital certificates, passwords, etc.).
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] Identity management (IdM) is the task of controlling information about users on computers.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] Such information includes information that authenticates the identity of a user, and information that describes data and actions they are authorized to access and/or perform.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] It also includes the management of descriptive information about the user and how and by whom that information can be accessed and modified.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] In addition to users, managed entities typically include hardware and network resources and even applications.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] The diagram below shows the relationship between the configuration and operation phases of IAM, as well as the distinction between identity management and access management.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] Access control is the enforcement of access rights defined as part of access authorization.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] Digital identity is an entity's online presence, encompassing personal identifying information (PII) and ancillary information.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] See OECD and NIST guidelines on protecting PII.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] It can be interpreted as the codification of identity names and attributes of a physical instance in a way that facilitates processing.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] A general model of identity can be constructed from a small set of axioms, for example that all identities in a given namespace are unique, or that such identities bear a specific relationship to corresponding entities in the real world.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] Such an axiomatic model expresses "pure identity" in the sense that the model is not constrained by a specific application context.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] In general, an entity (real or virtual) can have multiple identities and each identity can encompass multiple attributes, some of which are unique within a given name space.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] The diagram below illustrates the conceptual relationship between identities and entities, as well as between identities and their attributes.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] In most theoretical and all practical models of digital identity, a given identity object consists of a finite set of properties (attribute values).
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] These properties record information about the object, either for purposes external to the model or to operate the model, for example in classification and retrieval.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] A "pure identity" model is strictly not concerned with the external semantics of these properties.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] The most common departure from "pure identity" in practice occurs with properties intended to assure some aspect of identity, for example a digital signature or software token which the model may use internally to verify some aspect of the identity in satisfaction of an external purpose.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] To the extent that the model expresses such semantics internally, it is not a pure model.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] Contrast this situation with properties that might be externally used for purposes of information security such as managing access or entitlement, but which are simply stored, maintained and retrieved, without special treatment by the model.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] The absence of external semantics within the model qualifies it as a "pure identity" model.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] Identity management can thus be defined as a set of operations on a given identity model, or more generally, as a set of capabilities with reference to it.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] In practice, identity management often expands to express how model content is to be provisioned and reconciled among multiple identity models.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] The process of reconciling accounts may also be referred to as de-provisioning.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] User access enables users to assume a specific digital identity across applications, which enables access controls to be assigned and evaluated against this identity.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] The use of a single identity for a given user across multiple systems eases tasks for administrators and users.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] It simplifies access monitoring and verification, and allows the organizations to minimize excessive privileges granted to one user.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] Ensuring user access security is crucial in this process, as it involves protecting the integrity and confidentiality of user credentials and preventing unauthorized access.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] Implementing robust authentication mechanisms, such as multi-factor authentication (MFA), regular security audits, and strict access controls, helps safeguard user identities and sensitive data.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] User access can be tracked from initiation to termination of user access.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] When organizations deploy an identity management process or system, their motivation is normally not primarily to manage a set of identities, but rather to grant appropriate access rights to those entities via their identities.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] In other words, access management is normally the motivation for identity management and the two sets of processes are consequently closely related.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] Organizations continue to add services for both internal users and by customers.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] Many such services require identity management to properly provide these services.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] Increasingly, identity management has been partitioned from application functions so that a single identity can serve many or even all of an organization's activities.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] For internal use identity management is evolving to control access to all digital assets, including devices, network equipment, servers, portals, content, applications and/or products.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] Services often require access to extensive information about a user, including address books, preferences, entitlements and contact information.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] Since much of this information is subject to privacy and/or confidentiality requirements, controlling access to it is vital.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] Identity federation comprises one or more systems that share user access and allow users to log in based on authenticating against one of the systems participating in the federation.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] This trust between several systems is often known as a "circle of trust".
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] In this setup, one system acts as the identity provider (IdP) and other systems act as service providers (SPs).
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] When a user needs to access some service controlled by SP, they first authenticate against the IdP.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] Upon successful authentication, the IdP sends a secure "assertion" to the SP.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] "SAML assertions, specified using a markup language intended for describing security assertions, can be used by a verifier to make a statement to a relying party about the identity of a claimant.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] In addition to creation, deletion, modification of user identity data either assisted or self-service, identity management controls ancillary entity data for use by applications, such as contact information or location.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] Putting personal information onto computer networks necessarily raises privacy concerns.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] Absent proper protections, the data may be used to implement a surveillance society.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] Social web and online social networking services make heavy use of identity management.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] Helping users decide how to manage access to their personal information has become an issue of broad concern.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] Research related to the management of identity covers disciplines such as technology, social sciences, humanities and the law.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] Decentralized identity management is identity management based on decentralized identifiers (DIDs).
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] Within the Seventh Research Framework Programme of the European Union from 2007 to 2013, several new projects related to Identity Management started.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] The PICOS Project investigates and develops a state-of-the-art platform for providing trust, privacy and identity management in mobile communities.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] SWIFT focuses on extending identity functions and federation to the network while addressing usability and privacy concerns and leverages identity technology as a key to integrate service and transport infrastructures for the benefit of users and the providers.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] Ongoing projects include Future of Identity in the Information Society (FIDIS), GUIDE, and PRIME.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] In each organization there is normally a role or department that is responsible for managing the schema of digital identities of their staff and their own objects, which are represented by object identities or object identifiers (OID).
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] The organizational policies and processes and procedures related to the oversight of identity management are sometimes referred to as *Identity Governance and Administration* (IGA).
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] How effectively and appropriately such tools are used falls within scope of broader governance, risk management, and compliance regimes.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] An **identity-management system** refers to an information system, or to a set of technologies that can be used for enterprise or cross-network identity management.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] Identity and access management systems are central to meeting regulatory requirements across multiple sectors that mandate controls over who can access sensitive information.
[src:external-secrets/identity-management] NIST Special Publication 800-53 includes comprehensive identity and access management controls in the AC (Access Control) and IA (Identification and Authentication) control families, providing the reference framework for federal agency IAM implementations.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] The External Secrets Operator extends Kubernetes with Custom Resources, which define where secrets live and how to synchronize them.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] The controller fetches secrets from an external API and creates Kubernetes secrets.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] If the secret from the external API changes, the controller will reconcile the state in the cluster and update the secrets accordingly.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] To understand the mechanics of the operator let's start with the data model.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] The SecretStore references a bucket of key/value pairs.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] But because every external API is slightly different this bucket may be e.g. an instance of an Azure KeyVault or a AWS Secrets Manager in a certain AWS Account and region.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] Please take a look at the provider documentation to see what the Bucket actually maps to.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] The idea behind the SecretStore resource is to separate concerns of authentication/access and the actual Secret and configuration needed for workloads.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] The ExternalSecret specifies what to fetch, the SecretStore specifies how to access.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] An ExternalSecret declares what data to fetch.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] It has a reference to a `SecretStore` which knows how to access that data.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] The controller uses that `ExternalSecret` as a blueprint to create secrets.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] The ClusterSecretStore is a global, cluster-wide SecretStore that can be referenced from all namespaces.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] You can use it to provide a central gateway to your secret provider.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] ESO instantiates an external API client using the specified credentials from the `SecretStore` spec.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] ESO creates an `Kind=Secret` based on the template provided by `ExternalSecret.target.template`.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] The `Secret.data` can be templated using the secret values from the external API.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] Each persona will roughly map to a Kubernetes RBAC role.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] Depending on your environment these roles can map to a single user.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] **Note:** There is no Secret Operator that handles the lifecycle of the secret, this is out of the scope of ESO.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] The External Secrets Operator runs as a deployment in your cluster with elevated privileges.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] It will create/read/update secrets in all namespaces and has access to secrets stored in some external API.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] Ensure that the credentials you provide give ESO the least privilege necessary.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] Design your `SecretStore`/`ClusterSecretStore` carefully!
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] Be sure to restrict access of application developers to read only certain keys in a shared environment.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] You should also consider using Kubernetes' admission control system (e.g.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] OPA or Kyverno) for fine-grained access control.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] You can run multiple controllers within the cluster.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] One controller can be limited to only process `SecretStores` with a predefined `spec.controller` field.
[src:external-secrets/introduction-overview] Please help us test the setup and/or document use-cases.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Key management concerns keys at the user level, either between users or systems.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] This is in contrast to key scheduling, which typically refers to the internal handling of keys within the operation of a cipher.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Successful key management is critical to the security of a cryptosystem.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Cryptographic systems may use different types of keys, with some systems using more than one.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] These may include symmetric keys or asymmetric keys.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] In a symmetric key algorithm the keys involved are identical for both encrypting and decrypting a message.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Keys must be chosen carefully, and distributed and stored securely.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Asymmetric keys, also known as public keys, in contrast are two distinct keys that are mathematically linked.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] They are typically used together to communicate.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Public key infrastructure (PKI), the implementation of public key cryptography, requires an organization to establish an infrastructure to create and manage public and private key pairs along with digital certificates.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] The starting point in any certificate and private key management strategy is to create a comprehensive inventory of all certificates, their locations and responsible parties.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] This is not a trivial matter because certificates from a variety of sources are deployed in a variety of locations by different individuals and teams - it's simply not possible to rely on a list from a single certificate authority.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Certificates that are not renewed and replaced before they expire can cause serious downtime and outages.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Once keys are inventoried, key management typically consists of three steps: exchange, storage and use.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Prior to any secured communication, users must set up the details of the cryptography.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] In some instances this may require exchanging identical keys (in the case of a symmetric key system).
[src:external-secrets/key-management] In others it may require possessing the other party's public key.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] While public keys can be openly exchanged (their corresponding private key is kept secret), symmetric keys must be exchanged over a secure communication channel.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Formerly, exchange of such a key was extremely troublesome, and was greatly eased by access to secure channels such as a diplomatic bag.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Clear text exchange of symmetric keys would enable any interceptor to immediately learn the key, and any encrypted data.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] The advance of public key cryptography in the 1970s has made the exchange of keys less troublesome.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Since the Diffie-Hellman key exchange protocol was published in 1975, it has become possible to exchange a key over an insecure communications channel, which has substantially reduced the risk of key disclosure during distribution.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] It is possible, using something akin to a book code, to include key indicators as clear text attached to an encrypted message.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] The encryption technique used by Richard Sorge's code clerk was of this type, referring to a page in a statistical manual, though it was in fact a code.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] The German Army Enigma symmetric encryption key was a mixed type early in its use; the key was a combination of secretly distributed key schedules and a user chosen session key component for each message.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] In more modern systems, such as OpenPGP compatible systems, a session key for a symmetric key algorithm is distributed encrypted by an asymmetric key algorithm.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] This approach avoids even the necessity for using a key exchange protocol like Diffie-Hellman key exchange.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Another method of key exchange involves encapsulating one key within another.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Typically a master key is generated and exchanged using some secure method.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] This method is usually cumbersome or expensive (breaking a master key into multiple parts and sending each with a trusted courier for example) and not suitable for use on a larger scale.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Once the master key has been securely exchanged, it can then be used to securely exchange subsequent keys with ease.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] This technique is usually termed key wrap.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] A common technique uses block ciphers and cryptographic hash functions.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] A related method is to exchange a master key (sometimes termed a root key) and derive subsidiary keys as needed from that key and some other data (often referred to as diversification data).
[src:external-secrets/key-management] The most common use for this method is probably in smartcard-based cryptosystems, such as those found in banking cards.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] The bank or credit network embeds their secret key into the card's secure key storage during card production at a secured production facility.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Then at the point of sale the card and card reader are both able to derive a common set of session keys based on the shared secret key and card-specific data (such as the card serial number).
[src:external-secrets/key-management] This method can also be used when keys must be related to each other (i.e., departmental keys are tied to divisional keys, and individual keys tied to departmental keys).
[src:external-secrets/key-management] However, tying keys to each other in this way increases the damage which may result from a security breach as attackers will learn something about more than one key.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] This reduces entropy, with regard to an attacker, for each key involved.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] A recent method uses an oblivious pseudorandom function to issue keys without the key management system ever being in a position to see the keys.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] However distributed, keys must be stored securely to maintain communications security.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Security is a big concern and hence there are various techniques in use to do so.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Likely the most common is that an encryption application manages keys for the user and depends on an access password to control use of the key.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Likewise, in the case of smartphone keyless access platforms, they keep all identifying door information off mobile phones and servers and encrypt all data, where just like low-tech keys, users give codes only to those they trust.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] In terms of regulation, there are few that address key storage in depth.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] "Some contain minimal guidance like 'don’t store keys with encrypted data' or suggest that 'keys should be kept securely.'" The notable exceptions to that are PCI DSS 3.2.1, NIST 800-53 and NIST 800–57.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] For optimal security, keys may be stored in a Hardware Security Module (HSM) or protected using technologies such as Trusted Execution Environment (TEE, e.g.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Intel SGX) or Multi-Party Computation (MPC).
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Additional alternatives include utilizing Trusted Platform Modules (TPM), virtual HSMs, aka "Poor Man's Hardware Security Modules" (pmHSM), or non-volatile Field-Programmable-Gate-Arrays (FPGA) with supporting System-on-Chip configurations.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] In order to verify the integrity of a key stored without compromising its actual value a KCV algorithm can be used.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] The major issue is length of time a key is to be used, and therefore frequency of replacement.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Because it increases any attacker's required effort, keys should be frequently changed.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] This also limits loss of information, as the number of stored encrypted messages which will become readable when a key is found will decrease as the frequency of key change increases.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Historically, symmetric keys have been used for long periods in situations in which key exchange was very difficult or only possible intermittently.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Ideally, the symmetric key should change with each message or interaction, so that only that message will become readable if the key is learned (*e.g.*, stolen, cryptanalyzed, or social engineered).
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Security: Vulnerability of keys from outside hackers, malicious insiders.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Availability: Ensuring data accessibility for authorized users.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Heterogeneity: Supporting multiple databases, applications and standards.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Governance: Defining policy-driven access control and protection for data.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Governance includes compliance with data protection requirements.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Key management compliance refers to the oversight, assurance, and capability of being able to demonstrate that keys are securely managed.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Compliance can be achieved with respect to national and international data protection standards and regulations, such as Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard, Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act, Sarbanes–Oxley Act, or General Data Protection Regulation.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] A *key management system* (KMS), also known as a *cryptographic key management system* (CKMS) or *enterprise key management system* (EKMS), is an integrated approach for generating, distributing and managing cryptographic keys for devices and applications.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] They may cover all aspects of security - from the secure generation of keys over the secure exchange of keys up to secure key handling and storage on the client.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Thus, a KMS includes the backend functionality for key generation, distribution, and replacement as well as the client functionality for injecting keys, storing and managing keys on devices.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Many specific applications have developed their own key management systems with home grown protocols.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] However, as systems become more interconnected keys need to be shared between those different systems.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] To facilitate this, key management standards have evolved to define the protocols used to manage and exchange cryptographic keys and related information.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] KMIP is an extensible key management protocol that has been developed by many organizations working within the OASIS standards body.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] The first version was released in 2010, and it has been further developed by an active technical committee.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] The protocol allows for the creation of keys and their distribution among disparate software systems that need to utilize them.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] It covers the full key life cycle of both symmetric and asymmetric keys in a variety of formats, the wrapping of keys, provisioning schemes, and cryptographic operations as well as meta data associated with the keys.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] The protocol is backed by an extensive series of test cases, and interoperability testing is performed between compliant systems each year.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] A list of some 80 products that conform to the KMIP standard can be found on the OASIS website.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] The security policy of a key management system provides the rules that are to be used to protect keys and metadata that the key management system supports.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] This protection covers the complete key life-cycle from the time the key becomes operational to its elimination.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] A public-key infrastructure is a type of key management system that uses hierarchical digital certificates to provide authentication, and public keys to provide encryption.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] PKIs are used in World Wide Web traffic, commonly in the form of SSL and TLS.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Group key management means managing the keys in a group communication.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Most of the group communications use multicast communication so that if the message is sent once by the sender, it will be received by all the users.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] The main problem in multicast group communication is its security.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] In order to improve the security, various keys are given to the users.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] Using the keys, the users can encrypt their messages and send them secretly.
[src:external-secrets/key-management] IETF.org released RFC 4046, entitled Multicast Security (MSEC) Group Key Management Architecture, which discusses the challenges of group key management.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The name *Kubernetes* comes from the Ancient Greek term κυβερνήτης, *kubernḗtēs* (helmsman, pilot), which is also the origin of the words *cybernetics* and (through Latin) *governor*.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] "Kubernetes" is often abbreviated with the numerical contraction "K8s", meaning "the letter K, followed by 8 letters, followed by s".
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Kubernetes assembles one or more computers, either virtual machines or bare metal, into a cluster which can run workloads in containers.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] It works with various container runtimes, such as containerd and CRI-O.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Its suitability for running and managing workloads of all sizes and styles has led to its widespread adoption in clouds and data centers.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] There are multiple distributions of this platform—from independent software vendors (ISVs) as well as hosted-on-cloud offerings from all the major public cloud vendors.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The software consists of a control plane and nodes on which the actual applications run.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] It includes tools like `kubeadm` and `kubectl` which can be used to interact with its REST-based API.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced by Google on June 6, 2014.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The project was conceived and created by Google employees Joe Beda, Brendan Burns, and Craig McLuckie.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Others at Google soon joined to help build the project including Ville Aikas, Dawn Chen, Brian Grant, Tim Hockin, and Daniel Smith.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Other companies such as Red Hat and CoreOS joined the effort soon after, with notable contributors such as Clayton Coleman and Kelsey Hightower.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The design and development of Kubernetes was inspired by Google's Borg cluster manager and based on Promise Theory.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Many of its top contributors had previously worked on Borg; they codenamed Kubernetes "Project 7" after the *Star Trek* ex-Borg character Seven of Nine and gave its logo a seven-spoked ship's wheel (designed by Tim Hockin).
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Unlike Borg, which was written in C++, Kubernetes is written in the Go language.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced in June, 2014 and version 1.0 was released on July 21, 2015.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Google worked with the Linux Foundation to form the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) and offered Kubernetes as the seed technology.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Google was already offering a managed Kubernetes service, GKE, and Red Hat was supporting Kubernetes as part of OpenShift since the inception of the Kubernetes project in 2014.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] On March 6, 2018, Kubernetes Project reached ninth place in the list of GitHub projects by the number of commits, and second place in authors and issues, after the Linux kernel.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Until version 1.18, Kubernetes followed an N-2 support policy, meaning that the three most recent minor versions receive security updates and bug fixes.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Starting with version 1.19, Kubernetes follows an N-3 support policy.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines a set of building blocks ("primitives") that collectively provide mechanisms that deploy, maintain, and scale applications based on CPU, memory or custom metrics.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Kubernetes is loosely coupled and extensible to meet the needs of different workloads.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The internal components as well as extensions and containers that run on Kubernetes rely on the Kubernetes API.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The platform exerts its control over compute and storage resources by defining resources as objects, which can then be managed as such.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Kubernetes follows the primary/replica architecture.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The components of Kubernetes can be divided into those that manage an individual node and those that are part of the control plane.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The Kubernetes master node handles the Kubernetes control plane of the cluster, managing its workload and directing communication across the system.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The Kubernetes control plane consists of various components such as TLS encryption, role-based access control (RBAC) and a strong authentication method, network separation, each its own process, that can run both on a single master node or on multiple masters supporting high-availability clusters.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The various components of the Kubernetes control plane are as follows.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Etcd is a persistent, lightweight, distributed, key-value data store (originally developed as part of CoreOS).
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] It reliably stores the configuration data of the cluster, representing the overall state of the cluster at any given point of time.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Etcd favors consistency over availability in the event of a network partition (see CAP theorem).
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The consistency is crucial for correctly scheduling and operating services.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The API server serves the Kubernetes API using JSON over HTTP, which provides both the internal and external interface to Kubernetes.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The API server processes, validates REST requests, and updates the state of the API objects in etcd, thereby allowing clients to configure workloads and containers across worker nodes.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The API server uses etcd's watch API to monitor the cluster, roll out critical configuration changes, or restore any divergences of the state of the cluster back to the desired state as declared in etcd.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] As an example, a human operator may specify that three instances of a particular "pod" (see below) need to be running, and etcd stores this fact.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] If the Deployment controller finds that only two instances are running (conflicting with the etcd declaration), it schedules the creation of an additional instance of that pod.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The scheduler is an extensible component that selects the node that an unscheduled pod (the basic unit of workloads to be scheduled) runs on, based on resource availability and other constraints.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The scheduler tracks resource allocation on each node to ensure that workload is not scheduled in excess of available resources.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] For this purpose, the scheduler must know the resource requirements, resource availability, and other user-provided constraints or policy directives such as quality-of-service, affinity/anti-affinity requirements, and data locality.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The scheduler's role is to match resource "supply" to workload "demand".
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Kubernetes allows running multiple schedulers within a single cluster.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] As such, scheduler plug-ins may be developed and installed as in-process extensions to the native vanilla scheduler by running it as a separate scheduler, as long as they conform to the Kubernetes scheduling framework.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] This allows cluster administrators to extend or modify the behavior of the default Kubernetes scheduler according to their needs.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] A controller is a reconciliation loop that drives the actual cluster state toward the desired state, communicating with the API server to create, update, and delete the resources it manages (e.g., pods or service endpoints).
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] An example controller is a ReplicaSet controller, which handles replication and scaling by running a specified number of copies of a pod across the cluster.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The controller also handles creating replacement pods if the underlying node fails.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Other controllers that are part of the core Kubernetes system include a DaemonSet controller for running exactly one pod on every machine (or some subset of machines), and a Job controller for running pods that run to completion (e.g. as part of a batch job).
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Labels selectors often form part of the controller's definition that specify the set of pods that a controller manages.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The controller manager is a single process that manages several core Kubernetes controllers (including the examples described above), is distributed as part of the standard Kubernetes installation and responding to the loss of nodes.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Custom controllers may also be installed in the cluster, further allowing the behavior and API of Kubernetes to be extended when used in conjunction with custom resources (see custom resources, controllers and operators below).
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] A node, also known as a worker or a minion, is a machine where containers (workloads) are deployed.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Every node in the cluster must run a container runtime, as well as the below-mentioned components, for communication with the primary network configuration of these containers.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] kubelet is responsible for the running state of each node, ensuring that all containers on the node are healthy.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] It takes care of starting, stopping, and maintaining application containers organized into pods as directed by the control plane. kubelet monitors the state of a pod, and if not in the desired state, the pod re-deploys to the same node.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Node status is relayed every few seconds via heartbeat messages to the API server.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Once the control plane detects a node failure, a higher-level controller is expected to observe this state change and launch pods on another healthy node.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] A container runtime is responsible for the lifecycle of containers, including launching, reconciling and killing of containers. kubelet interacts with container runtimes via the Container Runtime Interface (CRI), which decouples the maintenance of core Kubernetes from the actual CRI implementation.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Originally, kubelet interfaced exclusively with the Docker runtime through a "dockershim".
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] However, from November 2020 up to April 2022, Kubernetes has deprecated the shim in favor of directly interfacing with the container through containerd, or replacing Docker with a runtime that is compliant with the Container Runtime Interface (CRI).
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] With the release of v1.24 in May 2022, the "dockershim" has been removed entirely.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Examples of popular container runtimes that are compatible with kubelet include containerd (initially supported via Docker) and CRI-O.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] kube-proxy is an implementation of a network proxy and a load balancer, and it supports the service abstraction along with the other networking operations.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] It is responsible for routing traffic to the appropriate container based on IP and port number of the incoming request.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, namespaces are utilized to segregate the resources it handles into distinct and non-intersecting collections.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] They are intended for use in environments with many users spread across multiple teams, or projects, or even separating environments like development, test, and production.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The basic scheduling unit in Kubernetes is a pod, which consists of one or more containers that are guaranteed to be co-located on the same node.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Each pod in Kubernetes is assigned a unique IP address within the cluster, allowing applications to use ports without the risk of conflict.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Within the pod, all containers can reference each other.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The container is the lowest level of a micro-service, which holds the running application, libraries, and their dependencies.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Kubernetes supports several abstractions of workloads that are at a higher level over simple pods.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] This allows users to declaratively define and manage these high-level abstractions, instead of having to manage individual pods by themselves.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Several of these abstractions, supported by a standard installation of Kubernetes, are described below.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] A ReplicaSet's purpose is to maintain a stable set of replica pods running at any given time.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] As such, it is often used to guarantee the availability of a specified number of identical Pods.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The ReplicaSet can also be said to be a grouping mechanism that lets Kubernetes maintain the number of instances that have been declared for a given pod.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The definition of a ReplicaSet uses a selector, whose evaluation will result in identifying all pods that are associated with it.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] A ReplicationController, similar to a ReplicaSet, serves the same purpose and behaves similarly to a ReplicaSet, which is to ensure that there will always be a specified number of pod replicas as desired.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The ReplicationController workload was the predecessor of a ReplicaSet, but was eventually deprecated in favor of ReplicaSet to make use of set-based label selectors.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Deployments are a higher-level management mechanism for ReplicaSets.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] While the ReplicaSet controller manages the scale of the ReplicaSet, the Deployment controller manages what happens to the ReplicaSet – whether an update has to be rolled out, or rolled back, etc.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] When Deployments are scaled up or down, this results in the declaration of the ReplicaSet changing, and this change in the declared state is managed by the ReplicaSet controller.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] StatefulSets are controllers that enforce the properties of uniqueness and ordering amongst instances of a pod, and can be used to run stateful applications.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] While scaling stateless applications is only a matter of adding more running pods, doing so for stateful workloads is harder, because the state needs to be preserved if a pod is restarted.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] If the application is scaled up or down, the state may need to be redistributed.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Databases are an example of stateful workloads.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] When run in high-availability mode, many databases come with the notion of a primary instance and secondary instances.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of ordering of instances is important.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Other applications like Apache Kafka distribute the data amongst their brokers; hence, one broker is not the same as another.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of instance uniqueness is important.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] DaemonSets are responsible for ensuring that a pod is created on every single node in the cluster.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Generally, most workloads scale in response to a desired replica count, depending on the availability and performance requirements as needed by the application.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] However, in other scenarios it may be necessary to deploy a pod to every single node in the cluster, scaling up the number of total pods as nodes are added and garbage collecting them as they are removed.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] This is particularly helpful for use cases where the workload has some dependency on the actual node or host machine, such as log collection, ingress controllers, and storage services.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] A Kubernetes service is a set of pods that work together, such as one tier of a multi-tier application.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The set of pods that constitute a service are defined by a label selector.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two modes of service discovery, using environment variables or using Kubernetes DNS.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Service discovery assigns a stable IP address and DNS name to the service, and load balances traffic in a round-robin manner to network connections of that IP address among the pods matching the selector (even as failures cause the pods to move from machine to machine).
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] By default a service is exposed inside a cluster (e.g., back end pods might be grouped into a service, with requests from the front-end pods load-balanced among them), but a service can also be exposed outside a cluster (e.g., for clients to reach front-end pods).
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Filesystems in the Kubernetes container provide ephemeral storage, by default.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] This means that a restart of the pod will wipe out any data on such containers, and therefore, this form of storage is quite limiting in anything but trivial applications.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] A Kubernetes volume provides persistent storage that exists for the lifetime of the pod itself.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] This storage can also be used as shared disk space for containers within the pod.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Volumes are mounted at specific mount points within the container, which are defined by the pod configuration, and cannot mount onto other volumes or link to other volumes.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The same volume can be mounted at different points in the file system tree by different containers.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] A common application challenge is deciding where to store and manage configuration information, some of which may contain sensitive data.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Configuration data can be anything as fine-grained as individual properties, or coarse-grained information like entire configuration files such as JSON or XML documents.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two closely related mechanisms to deal with this need, known as ConfigMaps and Secrets, both of which allow for configuration changes to be made without requiring an application rebuild.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The data from ConfigMaps and Secrets will be made available to every single instance of the application to which these objects have been bound via the Deployment.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] A Secret and/or a ConfigMap is sent to a node only if a pod on that node requires it, which will only be stored in memory on the node.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Once the pod that depends on the Secret or ConfigMap is deleted, the in-memory copy of all bound Secrets and ConfigMaps are deleted as well.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Mounted within a volume accessible within the container's filesystem, which supports automatic reloading without restarting the container.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The biggest difference between a Secret and a ConfigMap is that Secrets are specifically designed for containing secure and confidential data, although they are not encrypted at rest by default, and requires additional setup in order to fully secure the use of Secrets within the cluster.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Secrets are often used to store confidential or sensitive data like certificates, credentials to work with image registries, passwords, and ssh keys.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Kubernetes enables clients (users or internal components) to attach keys called labels to any API object in the system, such as pods and nodes.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Correspondingly, label selectors are queries against labels that resolve to matching objects.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] When a service is defined, one can define the label selectors that will be used by the service router/load balancer to select the pod instances that the traffic will be routed to.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Thus, simply changing the labels of the pods or changing the label selectors on the service can be used to control which pods get traffic and which don't, which can be used to support various deployment patterns like blue–green deployments or A/B testing.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] This capability to dynamically control how services utilize implementing resources provides a loose coupling within the infrastructure.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Just like labels, field selectors also let one select Kubernetes resources.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Unlike labels, the selection is based on the attribute values inherent to the resource being selected, rather than user-defined categorization.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] `metadata.name` and `metadata.namespace` are field selectors that will be present on all Kubernetes objects.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Other selectors that can be used depend on the object/resource type.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Add-ons are additional features of the Kubernetes cluster implemented as applications running within it.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The pods may be managed by Deployments, ReplicationControllers, and so on.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Cluster DNS is a DNS server, in addition to the other DNS server(s) in the environment, which serves DNS records for Kubernetes services.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Containers started by Kubernetes automatically include this DNS server in their DNS searches.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] This is a general purpose, web-based UI for Kubernetes clusters.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] It allows administrators to manage and troubleshoot applications running in the cluster, as well as the cluster itself.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Container Resource Monitoring records metrics about containers in a central database, and provides a UI for browsing that data.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Kubernetes cost monitoring applications allow breakdown of costs by pods, nodes, namespaces, and labels.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] To prevent the loss of event data in the event of node or pod failures, container logs can be saved to a central log store with a search/browsing interface.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides no native storage for log data, but one can integrate many existing logging solutions into the Kubernetes cluster.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Containers emerged as a way to make software portable.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The container contains all the packages needed to run a service.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The provided file system makes containers extremely portable and easy to use in development.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] A container can be moved from development to test or production with no or relatively few configuration changes.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Historically Kubernetes was suitable only for stateless services.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] However, many applications have a database, which requires persistence, leading to the creation of persistent storage for Kubernetes.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Implementing persistent storage for containers is one of the top challenges of Kubernetes administrators, DevOps and cloud engineers.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Containers may be ephemeral, but more and more of their data is not, so one needs to ensure the data's survival in case of container termination or hardware failure.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] When deploying containers with Kubernetes or containerized applications, organizations often realize that they need persistent storage.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] They need to provide fast and reliable storage for databases, root images and other data used by the containers.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] In addition to the landscape, the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF), has published other information about Kubernetes Persistent Storage including a blog helping to define the container attached storage pattern.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] This pattern can be thought of as one that uses Kubernetes itself as a component of the storage system or service.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Container Attached Storage is a type of data storage that emerged as Kubernetes gained prominence.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The Container Attached Storage approach or pattern relies on Kubernetes itself for certain capabilities while delivering primarily block, file, object and interfaces to workloads running on Kubernetes.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Common attributes of Container Attached Storage include the use of extensions to Kubernetes, such as custom resource definitions, and the use of Kubernetes itself for functions that otherwise would be separately developed and deployed for storage or data management.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Examples of functionality delivered by custom resource definitions or by Kubernetes itself include retry logic, delivered by Kubernetes itself, and the creation and maintenance of an inventory of available storage media and volumes, typically delivered via a custom resource definition.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] In Kubernetes version 1.9, the initial Alpha release of Container Storage Interface (CSI) was introduced.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Previously, storage volume plug-ins were included in the Kubernetes distribution.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] By creating a standardized CSI, the code required to interface with external storage systems was separated from the core Kubernetes code base.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Just one year later, the CSI feature was made Generally Available (GA) in Kubernetes.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] A key component of the Kubernetes control plane is the API Server, which exposes an HTTP API that can be invoked by other parts of the cluster as well as end users and external components.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] This API is a REST API and is declarative in nature, and is the same API exposed to the control plane.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The API server is backed by etcd to store all records persistently.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, all objects serve as the "record of intent" of the cluster's state, and are able to define the desired state that the writer of the object wishes for the cluster to be in.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] All objects in Kubernetes are subject to the same API conventions.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API can be extended using *Custom Resources*, which represent objects that are not part of the standard Kubernetes installation.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] These custom resources are declared using *Custom Resource Definitions* (CRDs), which is a kind of resource that can be dynamically registered and unregistered without shutting down or restarting a cluster that is currently running.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Custom controllers are another extension mechanism that interact with the Kubernetes API, similar to the default controllers in the standard pre-installed Kubernetes controller manager.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] These controllers may interact with custom resources to allow for a declarative API: users may declare the desired state of the system via the custom resources, and it is the responsibility of the custom controller to observe the change and reconcile it.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The combination of custom resources and custom controllers are often referred to as a *Kubernetes* *Operator*.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The key use case for operators are to capture the aim of a human operator who is managing a service or set of services and to implement them using automation, and with a declarative API supporting this automation.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Human operators who look after specific applications and services have deep knowledge of how the system ought to behave, how to deploy it, and how to react if there are problems.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Examples of problems solved by operators include taking and restoring backups of that application's state, and handling upgrades of the application code alongside related changes such as database schemas or extra configuration settings.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Several notable projects under the Cloud Native Computing Foundation's incubation program follow the operator pattern to extend Kubernetes, including Argo, Open Policy Agent and Istio.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines the following strategies for controlling access to its API.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API server listens on a TCP port that serves HTTPS traffic, in order to enforce transport layer security (TLS) using CA certificates.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] In older versions of Kubernetes, the API server supported listening on both HTTP and HTTPS ports (with the HTTP port number having no transport security whatsoever).
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] This was deprecated in v1.10 and eventually dropped support in v1.20 of Kubernetes.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Users are typically expected to indicate and define cluster URL details along with the necessary credentials in a *kubeconfig* file, which are natively supported by other Kubernetes tools like kubectl and the official Kubernetes client libraries.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] *Attribute-based access control (ABAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users through the use of defined access control policies which combine attributes together.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] *Role-based access control (RBAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users based on roles that are granted to the user, where each role defines a list of actions that are allowed.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] *Webhook mode*: Queries a REST API service to determine if a user is authorized to perform a given action.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The same API design principles have been used to define an API to harness a program in order to create, configure, and manage Kubernetes clusters.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] A key concept embodied in the API is using Infrastructure as Software, or the notion that the Kubernetes cluster infrastructure is itself a resource / object that can be managed just like any other Kubernetes resources.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Similarly, machines that make up the cluster are also treated as a Kubernetes resource.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The API has two pieces – the core API, and a provider implementation.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] The provider implementation consists of cloud-provider specific functions that let Kubernetes provide the cluster API in a fashion that is well-integrated with the cloud-provider's services and resources.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Kubernetes is commonly used as a way to host a microservice-based implementation, because it and its associated ecosystem of tools provide all the capabilities needed to address key concerns of any microservice architecture.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] A common criticism of Kubernetes is that it is too complex.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] Various vendors offer Kubernetes-based platforms or infrastructure as a service (IaaS) that deploy Kubernetes.
[src:external-secrets/kubernetes] These are typically categorized according to open-source, commercial or managed distributions.
[src:external-secrets/latest] The goal of External Secrets Operator is to synchronize secrets from external APIs into Kubernetes.
[src:external-secrets/latest] ESO is a collection of custom API resources - `ExternalSecret`, `SecretStore` and `ClusterSecretStore` that provide a user-friendly abstraction for the external API that stores and manages the lifecycle of the secrets for you.
[src:external-secrets/latest] To get started, please read through API overview this should give you a high-level overview to understand the API and use-cases.
[src:external-secrets/latest] After that please follow one of our guides to get a jump start using the operator.
[src:external-secrets/latest] See our getting started guide for installation instructions.
[src:external-secrets/latest] For a complete reference of the API types please refer to our API Reference.
